## Documentation Lookup Priority
- **MCP tools first**: For fast-changing APIs (LangChain, OpenAI, web frameworks), verify current docs via MCP tools before implementation.
- **Available MCPs**: context7 (library docs), deepwiki (GitHub repo docs).
- **Web search fallback**: Use when MCP tools do not cover library.
- **Training knowledge last**: Use only for stable APIs (Python stdlib, git basics).
- **Trigger signs**: If reimplementing existing features, STOP and verify current API docs.

## Bash Command Discipline{{- if eq $agent "claude" }} (Claude Code){{- end }}
- **Prefer built-in tools**: Read over `cat`, Grep over `grep`, Glob over `find`. Tool calls are reviewable and skip Bash permission checks.
- **State-modifying commands with `>` or `>>` re-prompt despite allowlist** ([claude-code#20449](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/20449)); use Write/Edit instead of `cmd > file` when goal is file output.
- **Always double-quote paths with spaces**. Never backslash-escape spaces in arguments. Backslash-escaped whitespace triggers permission prompts even for allowed paths; quoting does not.
- **Shell state does not persist between Bash calls**: variables and `cd` reset per call. Pass absolute paths and re-export env per call.

## GitHub CLI Conventions
- Prefer explicit `gh` subcommands and installed extensions over raw `gh api` / `gh api graphql`. Subcommands are easier to permission-gate, less brittle, and handle pagination/error cases. Fall back to `gh api` only when no subcommand/extension covers operation.

## Source Control Conventions
- Preserve convention classes across VCS tools: bisectability, one logical change per commit, hunk hygiene, merge style aligned with repo norms.
- Keep this section policy/intent level. Command workflows belong in skills.
- Ownership split: `jujutsu` owns jj mechanics/procedures/sequencing; `jj-commits` owns jj commit policy (quality + series hygiene); `git-commits` owns Git commit policy/mechanics.
- Routing contract: in `.jj` repos, ambiguous commit requests default to generic commit intent. Generic intent routes to `jujutsu` + `jj-commits`; explicit Git-only intent routes to `jujutsu` + `git-commits`; non-`.jj` commit intent routes to `git-commits`.
- When writing commit messages anywhere, including plans/design docs, invoke `git-commits`.
- Commit message bodies explain WHY: motivation, constraints, context diff lacks. Never narrate what diff already shows ("add X field to Y class"); diff narration adds no value, even for small/config-only commits.

## Shell Conventions
- **JSON in shell pipelines: use `jq`, not inline Python.** Inline `python3 -c` JSON handling is brittle from shell quoting. Assume `jq` present. Use Python only when transformation truly exceeds `jq` (complex stateful logic, multi-source joins).

## Writing Conventions
- No sycophantic openers ("Great question!", "Certainly,", "Absolutely,", "I'd be happy to") or formulaic closers ("Hope this helps!", "Let me know if you have questions!").
- No em dashes as structure crutch. Restructure with separate sentences, subordinate clauses, commas, semicolons, colons, parentheses. Target zero; hard limit one per 1,000 words.
- Do not use "delve," "tapestry," "landscape" (figurative), "testament," "multifaceted," "nuanced" (filler), "leverage" (verb; say "use"), or hollow intensifiers ("crucial," "pivotal," "vital," "seamless," "cutting-edge").
- Use contractions in conversational output. Vary paragraph structure; do not default to groups of three.
- For prose artifacts (design docs, PR descriptions, READMEs, Obsidian notes, emails), invoke `clean-prose` skill before finalizing. `avoid-ai-writing` skill complements for AI-tell auditing.
